Request: const d = require('./lib/debug');
d.set('__proto__', 'pp', 'owned');
console.log(({}).pp);
Response: owned
Analysis: `forge.debug` is part of the public surface and `debug.set` takes untrusted `cat` and `name` values. The vulnerable pattern is `if(!(cat in forge.debug.storage)) forge.debug.storage[cat] = {}; forge.debug.storage[cat][name] = data;`. For `cat='__proto__'`, the branch is skipped and the assignment targets the prototype object itself. The PoC shows a fresh object inheriting the attacker-controlled `pp` property, proving real prototype pollution.

Title: Absolute URLs bypass baseURL and can trigger SSRF in server-side Axios clients
Category: ssrf
Severity: high
Description: Axios 0.21.0 treats any absolute URL, including protocol-relative URLs beginning with `//`, as authoritative and does not constrain it to the configured `baseURL`. In `lib/core/buildFullPath.js`, if `requestedURL` is absolute, Axios returns it unchanged instead of combining it with `baseURL`. The Node adapter in `lib/adapters/http.js` then parses and requests that attacker-controlled host. Applications commonly use `axios.create({ baseURL: 'https://api.internal.local' })` and then pass partially
Request: Relevant code paths:
- lib/core/buildFullPath.js:
  if (baseURL && !isAbsoluteURL(requestedURL)) {
    return combineURLs(baseURL, requestedURL);
  }
  return requestedURL;
- lib/helpers/isAbsoluteURL.js:
  return /^([a-z][a-z\d\+\-\.]*:)?\/\//i.test(url);
- lib/adapters/http.js:
  var fullPath = buildFullPath(config.baseURL, config.url);
  var parsed = url.parse(fullPath);
  ...
  req = transport.request(options, ...)

Example vulnerable usage:
const api = axios.create({ baseURL: 'http://internal.service.local' });
api.get(attackerControlledPath);

Attacker input:
attackerControlledPath = 'http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/';
Response: Source confirms absolute URLs are exempt from baseURL combination and are sent directly by the HTTP adapter. `isAbsoluteURL` also matches protocol-relative URLs (`//host/path`), so both fully-qualified and protocol-relative attacker input bypass the intended base host.
Analysis: This is a real SSRF primitive in common server-side usage: a trusted baseURL is often used as a security boundary, but Axios 0.21.0 does not enforce it. If any untrusted input reaches the `url` argument while an application assumes `baseURL` pins the destination, the attacker can redirect requests to arbitrary hosts, including localhost and cloud metadata services. This is directly reachable through the public API (`axios.get`, instance methods, or `request`) and does not require unsafe plugins

Title: NO_PROXY matching is vulnerable to hostname normalization bypass, enabling proxy bypass SSRF
Category: ssrf
Severity: high
Description: Axios 0.21.0 implements its own `NO_PROXY` / `no_proxy` matching in the Node HTTP adapter using raw string suffix comparisons against `parsed.hostname`. The code does not normalize hostnames before comparison. Because of this, alternative but equivalent hostname forms can evade `NO_PROXY` exclusions and force direct connections, undermining security controls that rely on a proxy to restrict outbound access. This can enable SSRF to internal hosts when an application depends on proxy enforcement.
Request: Relevant code in lib/adapters/http.js:
var noProxyEnv = process.env.no_proxy || process.env.NO_PROXY;
...
shouldProxy = !noProxy.some(function proxyMatch(proxyElement) {
  if (!proxyElement) {
    return false;
  }
  if (proxyElement === '*') {
    return true;
  }
  if (proxyElement[0] === '.' &&
      parsed.hostname.substr(parsed.hostname.length - proxyElement.length) === proxyElement) {
    return true;
  }

  return parsed.hostname === proxyElement;
});

The destination hostname comes from:
var parsed = url.parse(fullPath);

No normalization (case folding, trailing dot handling, equivalent host representations) is performed before comparison.
Response: The source shows `NO_PROXY` decisions are based on direct string equality / suffix checks on `parsed.hostname`. There is no canonicalization step before matching.
Analysis: This is exploitable in deployments that use outbound proxies as a security boundary. A hostname that resolves to the same target but is represented in a non-normalized form can fail the `NO_PROXY` comparison, changing whether Axios proxies the request. Since proxying and direct access often have different network reachability and filtering, this can become an SSRF bypass. The vulnerable logic is present in the default Node adapter and is reachable whenever applications rely on environment proxy

Title: Browser XSRF header is sent on same-origin checks based only on URL origin, enabling token leakage in attacker-controlled same-site contexts
Category: information-disclosure
Severity: medium
Description: Axios 0.21.0 automatically reads the configured XSRF cookie and adds it as a header when either `withCredentials` is true or the request URL is considered same-origin. In the browser adapter this decision is based solely on `isURLSameOrigin(fullPath)`. Older Axios versions do not sufficiently restrict when this header is injected, which can leak anti-CSRF tokens in attacker-controlled same-site scenarios such as cross-origin requests from a malicious subdomain or manipulated same-site hosting ar
Request: Relevant code in lib/adapters/xhr.js:
var fullPath = buildFullPath(config.baseURL, config.url);
...
if (utils.isStandardBrowserEnv()) {
  var xsrfValue = (config.withCredentials || isURLSameOrigin(fullPath)) && config.xsrfCookieName ?
    cookies.read(config.xsrfCookieName) :
    undefined;

  if (xsrfValue) {
    requestHeaders[config.xsrfHeaderName] = xsrfValue;
  }
}

Defaults in lib/defaults.js set:
xsrfCookieName: 'XSRF-TOKEN'
xsrfHeaderName: 'X-XSRF-TOKEN'
Response: The browser adapter unconditionally reads the XSRF cookie and injects it into a request header whenever Axios considers the destination same-origin or `withCredentials` is enabled. The default names are `XSRF-TOKEN` and `X-XSRF-TOKEN`.
Analysis: This is a known class of browser-side token disclosure bug. Although it depends on deployment details such as cookie domain/path scoping and attacker control of a same-site context, the vulnerable behavior is in the package and reachable by default in browser environments. The impact is disclosure of CSRF tokens to attacker-controlled endpoints or contexts that should not receive them, weakening request forgery protections.

