  catch(e){ console.log('err', String(re), e.message); }
}
NODE
Response: The process timed out when `qs.parse` was invoked with a catastrophic-backtracking delimiter regex on a long attacker-controlled string (`spawnSync /bin/bash ETIMEDOUT`). A milder regex-delimiter benchmark also showed multi-second CPU consumption: `/[;,] */ ms 2248`, `/(,|;)+/ ms 4463`, `/(?:;|,\s*)/ ms 2222` on a repeated input string.
Analysis: `parse` explicitly allows RegExp delimiters (`options.delimiter = typeof options.delimiter === 'string' || utils.isRegExp(options.delimiter) ? options.delimiter : defaults.delimiter;`). `parseValues` then calls `cleanStr.split(options.delimiter, limit)`. In JavaScript, `String.prototype.split` with a pathological regex can trigger catastrophic backtracking. Because this package performs no restriction on regex complexity, applications that make delimiter configurable can be DoSed remotely. Impac

