Title: HTTP response splitting via unsanitized Sec-WebSocket-Protocol reflection in server handshake
Category: output-manipulation
Severity: medium
Description: In ws@7.4.5, `WebSocketServer.completeUpgrade()` reads the client-controlled `Sec-WebSocket-Protocol` header, splits it with `protocol.trim().split(/ *, */)`, and, when no custom `handleProtocols` hook is provided, reflects the first token directly into the HTTP upgrade response with `headers.push(`Sec-WebSocket-Protocol: ${protocol}`)`. There is no validation that the selected protocol token conforms to the WebSocket token grammar and no CR/LF stripping before writing headers with `socket.write
Request: Attacker-controlled input path in `lib/websocket-server.js`:
```js
let protocol = req.headers['sec-websocket-protocol'];
if (protocol) {
  protocol = protocol.trim().split(/ *, */);
  if (this.options.handleProtocols) {
    protocol = this.options.handleProtocols(protocol, req);
  } else {
    protocol = protocol[0];
  }
  if (protocol) {
    headers.push(`Sec-WebSocket-Protocol: ${protocol}`);
