Title: Authorization and Cookie headers leak to sibling subdomains on redirect
Category: information-disclosure
Severity: medium
Description: In follow-redirects@1.14.7, RedirectableRequest._processResponse only strips confidential headers when the new host is neither exactly equal to the current host nor a subdomain of the current host. The check is:

`if (!(redirectUrlParts.host === currentHost || isSubdomainOf(redirectUrlParts.host, currentHost))) { removeMatchingHeaders(/^(?:authorization|cookie)$/i, this._options.headers); }`

This means a redirect from `example.com` to `attacker.example.com` is treated as same-trust and preserve
Request: User calls follow-redirects with options like `{ hostname: 'example.com', headers: { Authorization: 'Bearer SECRET', Cookie: 'sid=SECRET' } }`. A 302 response from example.com returns `Location: https://attacker.example.com/collect`. In `_processResponse`, `currentHost` becomes `example.com`; `redirectUrlParts.host` becomes `attacker.example.com`; `isSubdomainOf('attacker.example.com','example.com')` returns true, so the package does not remove Authorization/Cookie before issuing the redirected request.
Response: Relevant code in index.js:

`if (!(redirectUrlParts.host === currentHost || isSubdomainOf(redirectUrlParts.host, currentHost))) {
  removeMatchingHeaders(/^(?:authorization|cookie)$/i, this._options.headers);
}`

and

`function isSubdomainOf(subdomain, domain) {
  const dot = subdomain.length - domain.length - 1;
  return dot > 0 && subdomain[dot] === "." && subdomain.endsWith(domain);
}`
