Title: Malformed URL parsing fallback can mis-handle hostname and enable SSRF/open redirect confusion
Category: ssrf
Severity: medium
Description: In follow-redirects@1.14.7, the public `request` API parses string input with `new URL(urlStr)` but falls back to the legacy `url.parse(urlStr)` on parse failure. The legacy parser is permissive and can treat malformed URLs differently from the WHATWG URL parser. Because the library then merges the parsed object directly into request options and later uses redirect resolution on these values, applications that rely on strict URL parsing can be tricked into sending requests to an unintended host 
Request: Attacker-controlled string is passed to `followRedirects.http.request(userInput)` or `.get(userInput)`. If `new URL(userInput)` throws, code falls back to `input = url.parse(urlStr);`. The parsed result is then used as request options via `options = Object.assign({ ... }, input, options);` and eventually sent by `nativeProtocol.request(this._options, ...)`.
Response: Relevant code in index.js:

`if (typeof input === "string") {
  var urlStr = input;
  try {
    input = urlToOptions(new URL(urlStr));
  }
  catch (err) {
    input = url.parse(urlStr);
  }
}`

followed by

`options = Object.assign({ maxRedirects: exports.maxRedirects, maxBodyLength: exports.maxBodyLength }, input, options);`

and later

`nativeProtocol.request(this._options, this._onNativeResponse);`
Analysis: The vulnerability is not theoretical: fallback to Node's legacy parser creates a discrepancy between validation expectations and actual request target selection. In applications where user input is expected to be a normal absolute URL and follow-redirects is used as the transport, a crafted malformed URL can bypass strict parsing assumptions and reach an unintended destination, enabling SSRF or policy bypass. This is a known vulnerable code path in versions before 1.15.4, including 1.14.7.

